§ Why ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ We give examples of metric spaces. ⦉
⦉

§ Example ⦉
<statement type='example'>
  ¶ ⦊
    ‖ Let $n$ be a natural number. ⦉

    ‖ Let $A$ be $𝗥^n$ and define $d: 𝗥^n × 𝗥^n → 𝗥$ by
      ◇ ⦊
        ‖ d(a, b) = √{(a_1 - b_1)^2 + ·s + (x_n - y_n)^2}. ⦉
      ⦉

      ‖ $(A, d)$ is a metric space. ⦉⦉
  ⦉
</statement>
<statement type='example'>
  ¶ ⦊
    ‖ Let $A$ be the unit circle in $𝗥^2$. ⦉

    ‖ So $A = \Set{x ∈ R^2}{x_1^2 + b^2 = 1}$. ⦉

    ‖ Let $d_1: A ×A → 𝗥$ defined by
      ◇ ⦊
        ‖ d(a, b) = √{(a_1 - b_1)^2 + (a_2 - b_2)^2}. ⦉
      ⦉⦉

    ‖ Let $d_2: A ×A → 𝗥$ defined as the arc length between
      the two points. ⦉

    ‖ Both $(A, d_1)$ and $(A, d_2)$ are metric spaces. ⦉
  ⦉
</statement>
<statement type='example'>
  ‖ Let $A = C([0, 1], 𝗥)$. ⦉

  ‖ Let $d_1: A ×A → 𝗥$ be such that
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ d_1(a, b) = \underset{x ∈ [0, 1]}{\max} \abs{a(x) -
        b(x)}. ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ Let $λ$ be the outer cover measure. ⦉

  ‖ Let $d_2: A ×A → R$ be such that
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ d_2(a, b) = ∈t_{[0, 1]} \abs{f - g} dλ. ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ Both $(A, d_1)$ and $(A, d_2)$ metric spaces. ⦉
</statement>
